Let $f\in C_0^oo(\R^d)$, $0<=a<b<oo$, and $h(t,x)=\I_{(a,b]}(t)f(x)$.

Consider \footnote{The form of which comes from the Duhamel's principle (see
\cite{LSU}) with considering $\I_{t>0}h$.}
$$
    v(t,x) = \int_0^t T_{t-s}h(s,\cdot)(x)ds
    = \int_0^t\int_{\R^d}p(t-s,x-y)h(s,y)dyds,
$$
where $p$ is the heat kernel, defined by
$$
    p(t,x) \defeq \I_{t>0}{1//(4\pi t)^{d/2}}e^{-{|x|^2//4t}}.
$$
One can easily check that $p_t=\Delta p$.

